rough the track. The message format mismatch between the frontend sending SDP as a string and the backend expecting JSON also needs alignment.\n\nLooking at the WebRTC implementation more carefully, `WriteVideoFrame` receives an `interface{}` type but never actually writes anything to the track. The frames just get discarded. And for the API server, it's not upgrading HTTP connections to WebSocket at all - it's just calling `c.Next()` which passes through to the next middleware, but there's nothing there to handle it.\n\nTo fix this properly, I'd need to integrate gorilla/websocket into the Gin handler and properly handle the WebSocket upgrade for signaling messages.\n\nNow looking at the Frontend issue - when it sends an offer via WebSocket, it's stringifying the SDP directly as the payload, but the backend webrtc.go is expecting to parse that payload as JSON. The SDP is just a raw string, not a JSON object, so the unmarshaling will fail when it tries to parse \"v=0\\r\\no=-...\" as JSON.\n\nThere's also a structural mismatch in the Go code - webrtc.go is calling `w.signalCh <- &SignalMessage{...}` to send signals through a channel, but the API server's handleWebRTCSignal function never actually reads from that channel or forwards the WebRTC signals to the client via WebSocket. These pieces aren't connected.\n\nThe fixes needed are: properly implementing WriteVideoFrame to actually write to the track, implementing the WebSocket handler in handleWebRTCSignal to read from signalCh and forward messages to clients, fixing the frontend's JSON-stringified SDP payload to match what the backend expects, and correcting the signaling flow so the backend properly marshals the SessionDescription instead of treating the SDP string as JSON.\n\nActually, stepping back - the whole WebRTC signaling infrastructure is fundamentally broken because the IPC channel between the API server and webrtc server isn't being used at all, the API server doesn't properly upgrade WebSocket connections, and WriteVideoFrame is a no-op. Rather than trying to patch this piecemeal, I should note that this is a systemic issue requiring a proper redesign of the signaling flow.\n\nFor the review though, I'll tackle the straightforward fixes: WriteVideoFrame should actually write to the track, handleWebRTCSignal should properly upgrade connections and relay messages, and the frontend/backend message format should be consistent. I also notice go.mod has a duplicate gocv dependency that should be cleaned up. Let me start with these targeted improvements.","signature":"7372fa6f55b46b72b57a1b4e8077bb5d9a5235df619401c1c12bc91102733e9e"}],"model":"MiniMax-M2.7","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":50821,"output_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":19028},"service_tier":"standard","context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c7030919-046f-4d40-9d16-8b74cebd40f3","uuid":"0c394cbc-4809-46de-a60f-1418510ae478"}
