{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"0613078e1e5982da67d9e04277114f45","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, so the frontend infrastructure looks reasonable. The vite config proxies `/api` and `/ws` to the Go server. The index.html has a navbar with router-links.\n\nNow let me focus on fixing the critical issues. I'll start with:\n\n1. Fix `WriteVideoFrame` in webrtc.go to actually write frames\n2. Fix the signaling path (api/server.go WebSocket handling + webrtc.go message handling)\n3. Fix the frontend message format\n\nThese fixes are within the existing architecture and don't require adding new dependencies.\n\nLet me start with `webrtc.go` - the `WriteVideoFrame` function needs to actually write H.264 data to the track. \n\nLooking at the current implementation, it just returns nil without doing anything. I need to make it write the packet data to the video track using Pion's WriteFrame method.\n\nThen for the signaling path, I need to handle the WebSocket upgrade in the API server properly so the client can exchange ICE candidates and session descriptions with the backend. I'm realizing the Gin framework's Next() method only invokes the next middleware in the chain, not an HTTP handler, so calling it in handleWebRTCSignal would just silently pass the request through without actually upgrading to WebSocket. This approach won't work—I need to either use a gorilla/websocket adapter for Gin or restructure how the API and WebRTC components interact.\n\nLooking at the actual usage pattern, the WebRTC instance is stored in api.ServerConfig and handleWebRTCSignal attempts to handle signaling, but there's no clear path for the WebSocket to actually communicate with the WebRTC instance. The architecture seems to require some bridging mechanism between the HTTP upgrade and the WebRTC component that isn't currently implemented. The simplest approach would be to use the gorilla/websocket package directly with Gin rather than implementing a custom upgrader, though that would require adding the dependency to go.mod. But I need to be careful here—I'm interpreting the task as focusing on review and documentation rather than making significant architectural changes to the IPC layer, especially since Go isn't even available in this environment to validate the changes.\n\nLet me identify what I can actually verify: the capture, encoder, MP4, storage, and API packages are all present and properly structured, but I'm noticing potential issues in the encoder's softEncoder.encode function which appears to be incomplete.\n\nLooking at the webrtc package, WriteVideoFrame is essentially a no-op that returns nil immediately, so it won't actually transmit any frames. The ipc/socket.go file uses net.ListenUnix correctly with a nil address parameter. There's also something odd in the webrtc handling where it attempts to unmarshal payload data but the logic seems unfinished.\n\nThe signal message handling has a format mismatch - the frontend sends an SDP string directly, but webrtc.go tries to unmarshal it as JSON, which will fail since the SDP is just plain text. Additionally, Gin doesn't natively support WebSocket upgrades without the gin-contrib/websocket middleware, so that portion of the code won't work as intended. The encoder module is also incomplete and would require FFmpeg CGO integration to properly handle video encoding.\n\nLooking at the core components, the recording system is fundamentally broken because the MP4 muxer lacks proper container format support, and the audio detection isn't receiving actual audio data to analyze. I should focus on identifying what I can realistically fix versus what requires architectural changes to the FFmpeg integration.","signature":"3beb13bef2e75c41a2f125dc6c7b82dbd0098caf2598ea565176cf5a55d41bdf"}],"model":"MiniMax-M2.7","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":53875,"output_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_toke