{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"0613083ea5eae4abadecf6f3f476f695","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me also fix the webrtc.go HandleSignal \"offer\" case - the frontend now sends `{ type: 'offer', payload: { type: 'offer', sdp: '...' } }`. But the backend does `SDP: string(msg.Payload)` which would be the JSON string of the payload, not the SDP field.\n\nWait, let me re-examine. After my frontend fix, the frontend sends:\n```js\nws.send(JSON.stringify({ type: 'offer', payload: { type: 'offer', sdp: pc.localDescription.sdp } }))\n```\n\nSo `msg.Payload` = `json.RawMessage` of `{ type: 'offer', sdp: '...' }`\n\n\nAnd then the backend extracts just the stringified JSON instead of parsing it to get the actual SDP value, so the remote description gets set with the wrong data format.\n\nActually, I should handle both cases more defensively in the frontend when receiving the answer, but the real issue is on the sending side - when we receive an offer, we're passing the entire payload string as the SDP instead of extracting the `sdp` field from within it.\n\nLet me trace through what happens: the frontend sends a stringified JSON object with the SDP nested inside, the backend receives this as raw bytes, and then tries to unmarshal it into a SessionDescription struct. The problem is we're treating the entire JSON string as the SDP value rather than parsing it first to extract the actual SDP field. The fix needs to happen in the backend when it processes the offer message - it should parse the JSON payload and extract the sdp field properly, not just cast the raw bytes directly to a string. I'm realizing I should make the backend more robust by having it parse the SDP field from the JSON payload directly, rather than relying on the frontend to format it correctly. This way the backend can handle the offer message regardless of how it's structured.","signature":"d3c93936e9c8d274f254d041903eb23c65bd81bedc17baa6cf6d9461d56